  "prompt": "Who invented immunofluorescence? What purpose does it serve?",
  "response": "Immunofluorescence was first developed in the 1940s by Albert Coons and colleagues. Albert Coons is often credited with pioneering this technique. Immunofluorescence is used to detect and visualize the presence and distribution of specific proteins or antigens in biological samples, such as cells or tissues, using antibodies conjugated to fluorescent dyes.\n\nThe primary purpose of immunofluorescence is to study the location and expression patterns of proteins within a cell or tissue. It is widely used in research and clinical diagnostics to analyze cellular components in various fields, including immunology, pathology, and molecular biology. The technique provides valuable insights into the function of proteins and their role in cellular processes and diseases.",
